where $\zeta_{t}$ is a normalized $r$-dimensional random variable with covariance matrix $\mathbb{E}\left(\zeta_{t} \zeta_{t}^{\prime}\right)=$ $I_{r}$, and assumed to be uncorrelated with the structural shocks; $\Omega_{t r}$ is a scaling matrix such that $\Omega=\Omega_{t r} \Omega_{t r}^{\prime}$ can be interpreted as the $r \times r$ covariance matrix of the measurement errors. Therefore, the covariance matrix of the proxies is $\Sigma_{z}:=\mathbb{E}\left(z_{t} z_{t}^{\prime}\right)=R_{z} R_{z}^{\prime}+\Omega$. The specification of $R_{z}$ in (7) is flexible and allows: $\Upsilon=0_{r \times(n-k)}$ under instrument exogeneity (thus, leading to the moment conditions (6)), and $\Upsilon \neq 0_{r \times(n-k)}$ when instruments are contaminated (i.e., when Condition (5) does not hold).

Given (7), the proxy-SVAR in (1) can be expressed as:

